cs.LG, cs.CV, cs.IT, cs.NA, cs.SI. 

The paper proposes a novel method to compute the L2-Wasserstein distance in a kernel space using the kernel trick, which is a general method in machine learning. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the most likely sub-category. The proposed approach is evaluated in identifying computerized tomography (CT) slices with dental artifacts in head and neck cancer, which involves image analysis and computer vision, making cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the theory of optimal transport, which falls under cs.IT (Information Theory). The use of the kernel trick suggests that the paper may also be relevant to cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
